    <h1>French TV Kenya: Lesson on French Verbs</h1>
    <h2>Introduction to Verbs</h2>
    <p>In French, verbs can be categorized into regular and irregular verbs. Regular verbs follow a consistent conjugation pattern, while irregular verbs have unique conjugations that must be memorized. In this lesson, we will focus on verbs in the <strong>present tense</strong>.</p>

    <h2>Regular Verbs</h2>
    <p>Regular verbs in French are grouped into three categories based on their endings: <strong>-er</strong>, <strong>-ir</strong>, and <strong>-re</strong>.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>-ER verbs:</strong> Examples: <em>parler</em> (to talk), <em>aimer</em> (to love), <em>manger</em> (to eat).</li>
        <li><strong>-IR verbs:</strong> Examples: <em>finir</em> (to finish), <em>choisir</em> (to choose).</li>
        <li><strong>-RE verbs:</strong> Examples: <em>vendre</em> (to sell), <em>attendre</em> (to wait).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Conjugation of Regular Verbs ending with ER in Present Tense</h3>
    <p>Example: Conjugation of the verb <em>parler</em> (to talk):</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Je parle</strong> (I talk)</li>
        <li><strong>Tu parles</strong> (You talk)</li>
        <li><strong>Il/Elle parle</strong> (He/She talks)</li>
        <li><strong>Nous parlons</strong> (We talk)</li>
        <li><strong>Vous parlez</strong> (You talk, formal/plural)</li>
        <li><strong>Ils/Elles parlent</strong> (They talk)</li>
    </ul>
<p2>Example2: Conjugaison du verbe <em>aimer<em/> (to like):</p2>
<ul>
        <li><strong>Je aime* J'aime</strong> (I like)</li>
        <li><strong>Tu aimes</strong> (You like)</li>
        <li><strong>Il/Elle aime</strong> (He/she likes)</li>
        <li><strong> Nous aimons</strong> (We like)</li>
        <li><strong> Vous aimez</strong> (You like)</li>
        <li><strong> Ils/Elles aiment</strong> (They like)</li>
</ul>
<h4>Conjugation of Regular Verbs ending with IR in Present Tense</h4>
    <p>Example: Conjugation of the verb <em>Finir</em> (to finish):</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Je finis</strong> (I finish)</li>
        <li><strong>Tu finis</strong> (You finish)</li>
        <li><strong>Il/Elle finit</strong> (He/She finish)</li>
        <li><strong>Nous finissons</strong> (We finish)</li>
        <li><strong>Vous finissez</strong> (You finish, formal/plural)</li>
        <li><strong>Ils/Elles finissent</strong> (They finish)</li>
    </ul>
<h5><strong>Conjugation of Regular Verbs ending with RE in Present Tenses</strong></h5>
    <p>Example: Conjugation of the verb <em>Attendre</em> (to wait):</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>J'attend</strong> (I wait)</li>
        <li><strong>Tu attends</strong> (You wait)</li>
        <li><strong>Il/Elle attend</strong> (He/She waits)</li>
        <li><strong>Nous attendons</strong> (We wait)</li>
        <li><strong>Vous attendez</strong> (You wait, formal/plural)</li>
        <li><strong>Ils/Elles attendent</strong> (They wait)</li>
    </ul>





    <h2>Irregular Verbs</h2>
    <p>Irregular verbs do not follow the regular conjugation patterns and must be learned individually. Here are some common irregular verbs:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Être</strong> (to be): Je suis, Tu es, Il/Elle est, Nous sommes, Vous êtes, Ils/Elles sont</li>
        <li><strong>Avoir</strong> (to have): J'ai, Tu as, Il/Elle a, Nous avons, Vous avez, Ils/Elles ont</li>
        <li><strong>Aller</strong> (to go): Je vais, Tu vas, Il/Elle va, Nous allons, Vous allez, Ils/Elles vont</li>
        <li><strong>Faire</strong> (to do/make): Je fais, Tu fais, Il/Elle fait, Nous faisons, Vous faites, Ils/Elles font</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Conjugation Practice</h3>
    <div class="exercise">
        <p><strong>Fill in the blanks:</strong></p>
        <ol>
            <li>Je ______ (parler) français.</li>
            <li>Nous ______ (finir) nos devoirs.</li>
            <li>Ils ______ (être) heureux.</li>
            <li>Tu ______ (avoir) un livre.</li>
            <li>Elle ______ (aller) à l'école.</li>
        </ol>
